-- PRESS DIGEST- Hong Kong - Dec 17
-- 
-- Tue Dec 16, 2014 09:31PM EST
-- None



Dec 17 (Reuters) - These are some of the leading stories in Hong Kong newspapers on Wednesday. Reuters has not verified these stories and does not vouch for their accuracy.

SOUTH CHINA MORNING POST  - The city's largest power supplier CLP Holdings Ltd <0002.HK> said it would increase its tariff for next year by 3.1 percent, far lower than the projected 11.8 percent put forward in its development plan. The move will generate estimated revenue of HK$1.3 billion ($168 million). (http://bit.ly/1wePQwS) - Hong Kong government's new homes target for the next 10 years has been boosted by 10,000 - meaning a total of 480,000 public and private units are planned by 2025. (http://bit.ly/1wXr328) - China lost US$1.25 trillion between 2003 and 2012 to illicit outflows including tax evasion, crime and corruption, the largest loss of money among 151 developing nations surveyed, according to a Washington-based advocacy group Global Financial Integrity that tracks such activities. (http://bit.ly/1DJyhKd)  THE STANDARD - Middle-aged citizens in Hong Kong look the most likely to buy health insurance under the proposed voluntary contribution scheme, which should ease the burden on the public health system, according to Undersecretary for Food and Health Sophia Chan Siu-chee. (http://bit.ly/13alT58) - Hong Kong could develop as an offshore yuan reinsurance centre, the Financial Services Development Council said. It estimated 22 billion yuan ($3.55 billion) more of reinsurance can be written in the Greater China region. (http://bit.ly/1zpuv4N)  HONG KONG ECONOMIC JOURNAL  - Hong Kong's export is expected to grow at a slower pace of 3 percent next year as compared to about 4 percent growth in value this year, according to Hong Kong Trade Development Council.